<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-a-cuboid">
    <title>Surface area of Prisms</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
        üîπ A prism is a Geometric object with two identical, parallel bases and straight sides connecting them.
    </p>
        
    <p>
        üîπA right prism is a geometric solid that has a polygon as its base and vertical faces perpendicular to the base.
        The base and top surface are the same shape and size. It is called a ‚Äúright‚Äù prism because the angles between
        the base and faces are right angles.
    </p>
    <p>
        üîπ Recall our defination for surface area which is the total area of the exposed or outer surfaces of a prism.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Types of Prisms}</m>
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{ Triangular Prism;}</m> It has a triangle at its base. 
    </p>
    <image width="50%">
        <shortdescription>Triangular Prism</shortdescription>
     <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}  
            % Define points
            \coordinate (A) at (0,0,0);
            \coordinate (B) at (3,0,0);
            \coordinate (C) at (1.5,2,0);
            \coordinate (D) at (0,0,3);
            \coordinate (E) at (3,0,3);
            \coordinate (F) at (1.5,2,3);

            % Draw the base (now at the bottom) with shading
            \fill[gray!30] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

            % Draw the base edges
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

            % Draw vertical edges
            \draw[thick] (A) -- (D);
            \draw[thick] (B) -- (E);
            \draw[thick] (C) -- (F);

            % Draw top face
            \draw[thick] (D) -- (E) -- (F) -- cycle;

            % Draw hidden lines
            \draw[dashed] (D) -- (F);
            \draw[dashed] (D) -- (E);
            \draw[dashed] (E) -- (F);
        \end{tikzpicture}
     </latex-image>
    </image>
    </sidebyside>
    <sidebyside>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Rectangular Prism;}</m> It has a rectangle at its base. A cube is a rectangular prism with all sides of equal length.
    </p>
    <image width="30%">
    <shortdescription> Rectangular Prism</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                 % Define cuboid dimensions
                \def\cubex{3} % Length
                \def\cubey{2} % Width
                \def\cubez{1.5} % Height

                % Draw the base face with grey fill
                \fill[gray!30] (0,0,0) -- ++(\cubex,0,0) -- ++(0,\cubey,0) -- ++(-\cubex,0,0) -- cycle;

                % Draw the front face
                \draw[thick,fill=gray!30] (0,0,0) -- ++(\cubex,0,0) -- ++(0,\cubey,0) -- ++(-\cubex,0,0) -- cycle;

                % Draw the top face
                \draw[thick] (0,0,\cubez) -- ++(\cubex,0,0) -- ++(0,\cubey,0) -- ++(-\cubex,0,0) -- cycle;

                % Draw the side face
                \draw[thick] (\cubex,0,0) -- ++(0,0,\cubez);
                \draw[thick] (0,\cubey,0) -- ++(0,0,\cubez);
                \draw[thick] (\cubex,\cubey,0) -- ++(0,0,\cubez);

                % Draw hidden lines
                \draw[dashed] (0,0,0) -- ++(0,0,\cubez);
                \draw[dashed] (0,0,\cubez) -- ++(0,\cubey,0);
                \draw[dashed] (0,\cubey,\cubez) -- ++(\cubex,0,0);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
    <image width="40%">
        <shortdescription>Rectangular (CUBE) Prism</shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Define points for the cube
                \coordinate (A) at (-1,-1,0);
                \coordinate (B) at (1,-1,0);
                \coordinate (C) at (1,1,0);
                \coordinate (D) at (-1,1,0);
                \coordinate (E) at (-1,-1,2);
                \coordinate (F) at (1,-1,2);
                \coordinate (G) at (1,1,2);
                \coordinate (H) at (-1,1,2);
                
                % Fill the base of the cube accurately
                \fill[gray!30] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; 

                % Draw edges of the cube
                \draw (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; % Bottom face (Base)
                \draw (E) -- (F) -- (G) -- (H) -- cycle; % Top face
                \draw (A) -- (E);
                \draw (B) -- (F);
                \draw (C) -- (G);
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
    </image>
    </sidebyside>
   <sidebyside>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Cylindrical Prism}</m> A cylinder has a circle as its base
    </p>
    <image width="30%">
        <shortdescription>Cylindrical prism</shortdescription>
     <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the top ellipse
            \draw (0,4) ellipse (1.5 and 0.5);

            % Draw the vertical sides of the cylinder (height doubled)
            \draw (-1.5,4) -- (-1.5,0);
            \draw (1.5,4) -- (1.5,0);

            % Draw the bottom ellipse (partially hidden)
            \fill[gray!30] (0,0) ellipse (1.5 and 0.5); % Shaded bottom base
            \draw[dashed] (0,0) ellipse (1.5 and 0.5);  % Dashed for hidden portion
        \end{tikzpicture}
     </latex-image>
    </image>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
        üîπExamples of right prisms are; a cylinder, a rectangular prism, a cube and a triangular prism.
    </p>
     
    </introduction>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Surface-area-of-a-cuboid">
        <title> Surface Area of a Cuboid.</title>
        <p>
        The surface area of a cuboid is the total area of all six faces of the cuboid. 
       
        </p>

        <p>
            When learning about area, we calculated the surface area of a cuboid.
             Since the opposite faces of a cuboid are identical, the surface area of a cuboid can be calculated by finding the area of each face and then adding them together.
        </p>

        <p>
            In this section, we will calculate the surface area of a cuboid from their nets.
        </p>

